research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0177.json:17:    "hypothesis": "Matched architecture probe on `routed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` under the unchanged mainline recipe (`K=128, EF=2, signum, lr=3.0e-3`). Final reconstruction remains `x_hat = U(Vx) + \u03a3_m pi_m c_m + \u03a3_i alpha_i^(1) b_i + \u03a3_j alpha_j^(2) b_j`; routing only perturbs stage-1/stage-2 support selection scores, while all decoded terms still come from static trunk, codebook, and residual libraries. This is `\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9` because LUTurbo/Lottable can export the low-rank trunk matrices, soft codebook vectors, and residual dictionary once, then execute `trunk lookup + codebook lookup + routed support selection + weighted sparse lookups + sum` online. The key question is whether router-driven support allocation is worth continuing in the low-EF feasible regime. Current cost accounting strongly suggests no: adding two full routers likely pushes encoder selection cost above the `1.5x h\u00d7n` hard cap, so the most informative outcome is a quick policy gate that rules this family out as a mainline candidate at `EF=2`.",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0177.json:18:    "summary": "Probe `routed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` as the one matched architecture change. It is LUTurbo-exportable (`\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9`) by the same static-library decomposition as the mainline, but is likely to be ruled out quickly because the extra routers make encoder selection cost exceed the hard budget, which would mean this family is not worth continuing on the current Pareto frontier.",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0177.json:23:    "self_review": "Single-variable discipline is preserved: only `ARCHITECTURE` changes, while `K`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR`, `OPTIMIZER`, and `LR` remain fixed to the mainline recipe. This probe is intentionally chosen to answer a clean architectural question under the new budget regime: whether routing is inherently worth carrying forward once low-EF cost feasibility is enforced.",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0177.json:50:      "At matched `K=128, EF=2`, routed two-stage soft-codebook is expected to exceed the encoder-cost cap because the two router projections add substantial full-dictionary selection cost on top of the mainline scorer.",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0177.json:51:      "Treat a fast policy rejection here as a useful architectural conclusion, not a runtime failure: the family is exportable but not cost-viable in the current feasible regime."
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0177.json:54:      "Return to the mainline `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` next round and tune exactly one cost knob such as `TRUNK_RANK`, `NUM_CODES`, or `STAGE1_RATIO`.",
research/history_archive/16_20260328_220351/round_summaries/round_0177.json:55:      "If this routed matched probe is policy-rejected as expected, mark routed two-stage soft-codebook as not worth continuing in the current low-cost regime unless a future single-variable cost-reduction round explicitly targets router cost."
